article.description:
Lauren Jackson's driving layup with
10 seconds left helped the Seattle Storm beat the Detroit Shock
81-79 and avoid one of the biggest collapses in league history.
article.headline: Storm blow 25-point lead, zap Shock in final seconds
article.linkText: Storm blow 25-point lead, zap Shock in final seconds
article.story:
AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- The Seattle Storm were thrilled to
make the playoffs, even if they nearly blew a 25-point lead to get
there.

Lauren Jackson's driving layup with 10 seconds left helped the
Storm beat the Detroit Shock 81-79 Tuesday night and avoid one of
the biggest collapses in league history.

"That's a great win for us," said Seattle coach Anne Donovan.
"We knew Detroit was too good to just quit."

After Swin Cash could only make one free throw with 31 seconds
left, Sue Bird, Cash's college roommate at Connecticut, took the
inbounds pass and waited. As the shot clock ran down, she found
Jackson inside, and the Australian Olympian spun past two defenders
for the go-ahead layup.

"I was just trying to get a basket," said Jackson, who
finished with 18 points. "I didn't care how."

Bird then jumped into Jackson's arms at midcourt as Detroit
called timeout.

"That was a tough, tough game," Bird said. "Obviously, you
don't ever want to give away that kind of lead, but we're very
happy right now."

Deanna Nolan missed a game-tying shot with three seconds left.

"Almost doesn't cut it," said Katie Smith, who had a game-high
25 points. "It's a loss."

Detroit now leads Indiana by just one game in the race for the
Eastern Conference's second seed, which would mean homecourt
advantage in a probable first-round matchup between the teams.

Seattle dominated the first half, hitting nine 3-pointers on its
way to a 53-31 halftime lead. Bird had 20 of her 24 points in the
half, including six 3-pointers.

"I don't think I've ever had a half like that in the pros,"
she said. "Maybe I had one in high school."

The Storm increased the margin to 56-31 in the first minute of
the third, but couldn't put Detroit away.

A Shock rally, sparked by a spectacular defensive play by Nolan,
pulled Detroit within 66-58 at the end of the third. She ran down
Bird in the open court and swatted her layup attempt off the
backboard and into the hands of teammate Plenette Pierson.

"I've seen her do that so many times to so many people, but I
thought I had enough room," Bird said. "Lesson learned. I should
have shot-faked."

Nolan's play even brought a smile to Donovan's face.

"That was special," she said. "Even our players were fired up
about that. They are all talking about it in the locker room."

Detroit kept coming in the fourth, beating the Storm to nearly
every rebound, and Cheryl Ford's basket pulled them within 73-71
with 4:01 to play.

After a Betty Lennox basket, Ford hit two free throws and Smith
drained a 3-pointer to give Detroit a 76-75 lead.

The teams traded the lead until Cash missed the second of her
free throws to leave the game tied at 79.

The Shock were trying to match their own league record for the
biggest comeback. Last season, they overcame a 35-10 deficit to
beat Los Angeles 79-73.

"Once again, we show our schizophrenia," Detroit coach Bill
Laimbeer said. "We decided we wanted to play basketball, not get
embarrassed. So we turned it around, but it wasn't good enough."
